In the implementation provided above, I have already used `pthread_mutex_t` for the mutexes. `pthread_cond_t` is used for condition variables to signal/broadcast waiting threads. There's no need to replace `pthread_cond_t` with `pthread_mutex_t` because they serve different purposes.

If you still want to have only mutexes and no condition variables, you will have to use a different synchronization mechanism. I recommend having separate mutexes for readers and writers and using reference counting to keep track of the number of readers. However, this may lead to a less optimal solution.

Here's an example implementation without `pthread_cond_t` (not recommended):

```c
#include "zc_io.h"

struct zc_file {
    void *ptr;
    off_t offset;
    size_t size;
    int fd;
    pthread_mutex_t all_mutex;
    pthread_mutex_t read_mutex;
    unsigned int readers;
    pthread_mutex_t write_mutex;
    int writing;
};

// ... 

const char *zc_read_start(zc_file *file, size_t *size) {
    pthread_mutex_lock(&(file->read_mutex));
    file->readers++;

    while (file->writing) { }

    if (file->offset + *size > file->size) {
        *size = file->size - file->offset;
    }

    const char *data = file->ptr + file->offset;
    file->offset += *size;

    pthread_mutex_unlock(&(file->read_mutex));

    return data;
}

