Assuming you have an excel file stored as a CSV file, you can use the following JavaScript code to check if a certain word exists in the contents of the file:

1. Import the csv-parser library:

```javascript
const csv = require('csv-parser');
const fs = require('fs');
```

2. Parse the CSV file:

```javascript
const results = [];

fs.createReadStream('yourfile.csv')
  .pipe(csv())
  .on('data', (data) => results.push(data))
  .on('end', () => {
    // code to check if the word exists in the contents
  });
```

3. Iterate through the contents and check if the word exists:

```javascript
let exists = false;

for (let i = 0; i < results.length; i++) {
  // Assuming you want to check the 'content' column
  const content = results[i]['content'];

  if (content.includes(wordToCheck)) {
    exists = true;
    break;
  }
}

if (exists) {
  console.log(`The word ${wordToCheck} exists in the contents`);
} else {
  console.log(`The word ${wordToCheck} does not exist in the contents`);
}
```

Note that you'll need to replace `yourfile.csv` with the actual name of your CSV file, and `wordToCheck` with the word that the user inputs.
